06912nam a22007095i 9780774853897DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748538977 a10.59962/97807748538972doi  a(DE-B1597)662051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aG246.V3.F76 1993eb 7aHIS0510002bisacsh04a910.9100aFrom Maps to Metaphors :bThe Pacific World of George Vancouver /ced. by Hugh Johnston, Robin Fisher. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (362 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tHow the Squamish Remember George Vancouver -- tIntroduction -- tJames Cook and the European Discovery of Polynesia -- tMyth and Reality: The Theoretical Geography of Northwest America from Cook to Vancouver -- tVancouver’s Survey Methods and Surveys -- tVancouver’s Chronometers -- tA Notable Absence: The Lateness and Lameness of Russian Discovery and Exploration in the North Pacific, 1639–1803 -- tNootka Sound and the Beginnings of Britain’s Imperialism of Free Trade -- tSeduction before Sovereignty: Spanish Efforts to Manipulate the Natives in Their Claims to the Northwest Coast -- tDangerous Liaisons: Maquinna, Quadra, and Vancouver in Nootka Sound, 1790–5 -- tArt and Exploration: The Responses of Northwest Coast Native Artists to Maritime Explorers and Fur Traders -- tKidnapped: Tuki and Hurl’s Involuntary Visit to Norfolk Island in 1793 -- tBanks and Menzies: Evolution of a Journal -- tThe Intellectual Discovery and Exploration of Polynesia -- tThe Burden of Terra Australis: Experiences of Real and Imagined Lands -- tAppendices: Vancouver’s Instruments, Charts, and Drawings -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the summers of 1792-94, George Vancouver and the crew of the British naval ships Discovery and Chatham mapped the northwest coast of North America from Baja California to Alaska. Vancouver's voyage was the last, and longest, of the great Pacific voyages of the late eighteenth century. Taking the art and technique of distant voyaging to a new level, Vancouver eliminated the possibility of a northwest passage and his remarkably precise surveys completed the outline of the Pacific. But to map an area is to appropriate it -- to begin to bring it under control -- and Vancouver's charts of the northwest coast were part of a process of economic exploitation and cultural disruption. Although he and the other great navigators of his age exercised no control over the ideas and enterprises spawned by their voyages, their names have come to symbolize the consequences of European expansion -- good or bad. From Maps to Metaphors grew out of the Vancouver Conference on Exploration and Discovery, held to observe the bicentennial of Vancouver's arrival on the Pacific northwest coast. It brings to light much of the new research on the discovery of the Pacific and illuminates the European and Native experience. The chapters are written from a variety of perspectives and provide new insights on many aspects of Vancouver's voyages -- from the technology employed to the complex political and power relationships among European explorers and the Native leadership. While it is no longer possible to 'celebrate' the arrival to the northwest coast of explorers such as Vancouver, their achievements cannot be overlooked. The charts, log books, journals, and specimens from these voyages are important sources of information and essential for the reconstruction of an image of the Pacific region and its people in the eighteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Expeditions & Discoveries.2bisacsh1 aArcher, Christon I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Alun C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinney, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrost, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, K.R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Hugh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLamb, W. Kaye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackay, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalmond, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Glyndwr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWyatt, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485389740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774853897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774853897/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Co